<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920128-0149</DOCNO><DOCID>920128-0149.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief:   Oryx Energy Has `Significant' Discovery   Of Oil and Natural Gas in Gulf of Mexico</HL><DATE>01/28/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   AHC ORX</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)OIL-SECONDARY (OIS)PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><NS>OIL-GAS DISCOVERIES (DSC)EARNINGS (ERN)PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   DALLAS -- Oryx Energy Co. said it made a &quot;significant&quot; oiland natural gas discovery in the Gulf of Mexico.   Its OCS-G 7462 No. 1 well flowed at a daily rate of 6,496barrels of oil and 24.5 million cubic feet of natural gascombined from two producing zones. The discovery well is thefirst test well in the Garden Banks 260 block of the Gulf infederal waters offshore Texas.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;We estimate gross potential reserves at 100 million to200 million equivalent barrels, making this our top priorityin the Gulf,&quot; said Robert L. Keiser, president and chiefoperating officer of Oryx.   Oryx said it owns a 50% working interest in the four-blockarea that includes Garden Banks 215 South and 259 through261. Amerada Hess Corp. owns the other half. Oryx said italso owns an interest in several adjacent blocks with otherpartners.   Separately, Oryx reported a loss of $40 million, or 54cents a share, for its 1991 fourth quarter, after a $35million restructuring charge and $22 million in losses onasset sales. The results compare with year-earlier net incomeof $140 million, or $1.61 a share, including a $50 milliongain on asset sales. Revenue fell to $370 million from $763million, primarily because of sharply lower oil and gasprices.   For the year, Oryx said net income was $19 million, oreight cents a share, including the restructuring charge andgains of $39 million on asset sales. For 1990, the companyreported net income of $225 million, or $2.26 a share, with$53 million in gains. Revenue for the year dropped to $1.6billion from $2.1 billion.   At a presentation to analysts in New York yesterday, Oryxexecutives said its spending on exploration, development andacquisition activities will drop to $380 million in 1992 fromthe $569 million it spent in 1991. The company also plans tocut its costs to about $1.36 billion in 1992, a 15% decreasefrom the $1.6 billion in total costs in 1991.   In 1991, Oryx reduced its debt to $2.36 billion from $2.92billion and plans to cut debt to less than $2 billion in1992.   Oryx shares closed at $25, up 25 cents, and Amerada Hessat $46, off 62.5 cents, both in New York Stock Exchangecomposite trading.</TEXT></DOC>